
[1]loosen

   LOOS'EN, v.t. loos'n. [from loose.]

   1. To free from tightness, tension, firmness or fixedness; as, to
   loosen a string when tied, or a knot; to loosen a joint; to loosen a
   rock in the earth.

   2. To render less dense or compact; as, to loosen the earth about the
   roots of a tree.

   3. To free from restraint.

   It loosens his hands and assists his understanding.

   4. To remove costiveness from; to facilitate or increase alvine
   discharges.

   Fear looseneth the belly.

    LOOS'EN, v.i. To become loose; to become less tight, firm or compact.
